./observer/logs/reviewer_iter-2_20260620T065454Z.log:1522:  - "prd/tech-design.md:25: On fcntl platforms, acquire() ignores an existing lock file containing a live PID unless another process currently holds a flock on the same inode. That contradicts the unchanged tests and existing semantics: test_acquire_already_locked_different_pid_alive writes PID 1 and expects acquire() to return False, but the proposed code would acquire the flock and return True."
./observer/logs/reviewer_iter-2_20260620T065454Z.log:1523:  - "prd/tech-design.md:55: release() unlinks the lock path even when this FileLockManager never acquired that project. Existing release() is a no-op for locks held by another PID; the proposed version can remove another process's lock file, and with flock this is dangerous because the lock remains on the unlinked inode while a new process can create and lock a new file at the same path."
./observer/logs/reviewer_iter-2_20260620T065454Z.log:1547:I’m going to record this as `REQUEST_CHANGES`: the revised plan fixed the earlier ownership check, but the proposed `release()` sequence unlocks before removing the path, which reopens the same unlinked-lock race it is trying to avoid.
./observer/logs/reviewer_iter-2_20260620T065454Z.log:1561:+  - "prd/tech-design.md:89: release() unlocks and closes the fd before unlinking the lock path. After LOCK_UN/os.close and before unlink, another process can open the same path, acquire the flock, write its PID, and then this release() call unlinks that other process's active lock file. The design should keep ownership of the path while removing it, e.g. unlink while still holding the flock and only then unlock/close, so a release cannot delete a successor's lock."
