./observer/logs/planner_iter-2_20260620T065333Z.log:397:**Problem**: Proposed `acquire()` skipped straight to `flock()` — if PID 1 was in the lock file but init didn't hold a flock, our flock would succeed and we'd steal the lock. Test `test_acquire_already_locked_different_pid_alive` would fail.
./observer/logs/planner_iter-2_20260620T065333Z.log:401:### Review Finding 2 — Fixed: `release()` only touches locks we own
./observer/logs/planner_iter-2_20260620T065333Z.log:403:**Problem**: Proposed `release()` unconditionally unlinked the lock file even when `project` wasn't in `_fds`, meaning calling `release("nonexistent")` could delete another process's lock file. On flock platforms this is particularly dangerous: the old process's lock stays on the orphaned inode while a new process creates + locks a fresh file at the same path.
