./observer/logs/planner_iter-1_20260620T065021Z.log:395:**Problem:** `acquire()` at `lock.py:57-72` has a classic TOCTOU race — between reading the lock file PID and writing our own, a concurrent process can read the same stale state, both believing they hold the lock.
./observer/logs/planner_iter-1_20260620T065021Z.log:401:**Stale locks:** Eliminated entirely — the kernel releases `flock` on process exit. PID-in-file becomes metadata only for `is_locked()` diagnostics.
./observer/logs/planner_iter-1_20260620T065021Z.log:405:- `release()` unlocks per-project via `flock` + unlink
./observer/logs/planner_iter-1_20260620T065021Z.log:407:- `is_locked()` continues working
./observer/logs/planner_iter-1_20260620T065021Z.log:416:**`acquire()`** — opens fd with `os.O_CREAT | os.O_RDWR`, calls `fcntl.flock(fd, LOCK_EX | LOCK_NB)`, catches `BlockingIOError` → returns `False`. On success, writes PID for diagnostics and stores fd in `self._fds[project]`.
./observer/logs/planner_iter-1_20260620T065021Z.log:418:**`release()`** — pops fd from `self._fds`, calls `fcntl.flock(fd, LOCK_UN)` then `os.close(fd)`, unlinks lock file with `missing_ok=True`.
