./reviews/code-review-codex.md:59:### L1: Classic TOCTOU race in `acquire()` (L2)
./reviews/code-review-codex.md:61:- **Description:** `acquire()` checks `if lock_path.exists()` (line 57), reads the PID, checks liveness, then writes the lock (line 72). Between the `exists()` check and the `write_text()` call, another process could acquire the lock. This is a textbook TOCTOU (Time-of-check, Time-of-use) race.
./reviews/code-review-codex.md:74:### L2: `release()` lacks PID ownership verification (L1)
./reviews/code-review-codex.md:76:- **Description:** `release()` unconditionally deletes the lock file without verifying that the current process owns it. If a stale lock is overridden by process A, process B (which originally held the lock) could release it later, removing A's lock. This becomes exploitable when combined with the TOCTOU race in `acquire()`.
./reviews/code-review-codex.md:77:- **Suggested Fix:** On `release()`, read the lock file and only delete if the PID matches `os.getpid()`.
./reviews/code-review-codex.md:197:| `lock.py` | `test_lock.py` (173 lines) | **Good.** Tests acquisition, re-entrant check, stale override, release, PID detection, multiple projects. Missing: concurrent race condition tests, `release()` ownership verification, empty lock file content. |
./reviews/code-review-claude.md:3:### [L2] Lock file acquisition has TOCTOU race condition | lock.py:57-72 | `FileLockManager.acquire()` checks if the lock file exists (line 57), reads the PID, checks liveness, then writes—all without any atomic operation or filesystem guard. Between the check and the write, another orchestrator process can acquire the lock. Two orchestrators may simultaneously believe they hold the lock. | Use `os.open(lock_path, os.O_CREAT | os.O_EXCL | os.O_WRONLY)` for atomic creation, or use `lock_path.touch(exist_ok=False)` which is safer. Fall back to PID-check only if the file already exists. Alternatively, use `fcntl.flock` on the open FD for kernel-enforced exclusive locking.
./reviews/code-review-claude.md:9:### [L2] No SIGINT/SIGTERM handler — lock leaks on interrupt | orchestrator.py:1-1123 | Despite documentation claiming "SEAN Ctrl-C (SIGINT → graceful shutdown)," there is no `signal.signal(signal.SIGINT, ...)` registered anywhere. A `KeyboardInterrupt` during `subprocess.run()` will propagate past the `finally` block in `run()` (line 203) ONLY if no cleanup is done between the exception and the frame unwind. If the interrupt arrives during `_run_state_machine()` or `_run_loop()`, the lock is released in the `finally` block. However, if the interrupt arrives during `subprocess.run()` inside a runner (which is called without a try/except), the exception propagates up to `_run_state_machine()` and then to the `finally` block—so the lock IS released, but there is no partial-state save or checkpoint. Worse: the orchestrator does not set `halt_signal` on SIGINT, so an Observer polling `state()` will never see a halt reason. | Register `signal.signal(signal.SIGINT, lambda s, f: self.halt("SIGINT"))` in `__init__` or at the start of `run()`. Wrap the body of `run()` in a `try: ... finally: self._lock_mgr.release(project_name)` (already done). Additionally save a checkpoint on halt before releasing the lock so resumption is possible.
