     2	
     3	## Problem
     4	`FileLockManager.acquire()` in lock.py:57-72 has a TOCTOU race:
     5	check exists → read PID → check liveness → write. Two processes
     6	can pass the check simultaneously.
     7	
     8	## Solution
     9	Replace PID-file polling with `fcntl.flock(LOCK_EX | LOCK_NB)`:
    10	- Atomic, kernel-enforced exclusive lock
    11	- Auto-released on process exit (no stale lock files)
    12	- Fall back to current PID-file behavior if `fcntl` unavailable
    13	
    14	## Implementation
    15	
    16	### acquire()
    17	1. Open lock file with `os.open(lock_path, os.O_RDWR | os.O_CREAT, 0o644)`
    18	2. Try `fcntl.flock(fd, fcntl.LOCK_EX | fcntl.LOCK_NB)`
    19	3. If success: store fd for release, return True
    20	4. If EAGAIN/EWOULDBLOCK: close fd, fall back to PID-file logic
    21	5. Store fd in `self._fds: dict[str, int]`
    22	
    23	### release()
    24	1. Look up fd in `self._fds`. If found:
    25	   - `fcntl.flock(fd, fcntl.LOCK_UN)`
    26	   - `os.close(fd)`
    27	   - `del self._fds[project]`
    28	   - `lock_path.unlink(missing_ok=True)`
    29	2. If no fd (PID-file fallback): use existing unlink logic
    30	3. If lock_path missing or held by another PID: no-op
    31	
    32	### is_locked()
    33	1. Try `fcntl.flock(fd, fcntl.LOCK_EX | fcntl.LOCK_NB)` on a test fd
    34	2. If EAGAIN: locked. Close fd, return True
    35	3. If success: not locked. Unlock, close, return False
